1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:04,587
# AI Weekly #11/2026

2
00:00:04,587 --> 00:00:07,462
March 9, 2026  Week 11.

3
00:00:07,462 --> 00:00:08,425
TL;DR.

4
00:00:08,425 --> 00:00:18,925
Anthropic vs. Pentagon: The US Department of Defense classified Anthropic as a "supply chain risk" — because Claude refuses to support autonomous weapons systems.

5
00:00:18,925 --> 00:00:24,787
Market response: #1 App Store in over 15 countries, 1M signups daily.

6
00:00:24,787 --> 00:00:26,950
Anthropic filed a lawsuit today  .

7
00:00:26,950 --> 00:00:39,225
22 Firefox bugs in 14 days: Claude Opus 4.6 analyzed 6,000 C++ files and found 14 high-severity vulnerabilities — better at finding than exploiting.

8
00:00:39,225 --> 00:00:41,150
Clear advantage for defenders

9
00:00:41,150 --> 00:00:57,125
GPT-5.4: 1-million-token context, native computer use, 75% on OSWorld (human level: 72.4%) — and 33% fewer hallucinations than GPT-5.2 .

10
00:00:57,125 --> 00:01:12,662
4,000+ jobs at Block: Jack Dorsey explicitly names AI as the reason — one of the first publicly traded companies to attribute mass layoffs directly and without PR spin to AI (AI causality partly disputed)

11
00:01:12,662 --> 00:01:19,950
Story of the Week: Pentagon Labels Claude a "Supply Chain Risk" — Users Respond with 1 Million Signups Daily.

12
00:01:19,950 --> 00:01:23,900
It started as a government decree and ended today with a lawsuit.

13
00:01:23,900 --> 00:01:38,625
On March 5, 2026, the US Department of Defense officially classified Anthropic as a "supply chain risk"  — the concrete trigger: Anthropic refused to make Claude available for autonomous weapons systems and mass surveillance.

14
00:01:38,625 --> 00:01:46,650
Defense Secretary Hegseth chose the wording precisely: not "unreliable," not "hostile," but supply chain risk.

15
00:01:46,650 --> 00:02:03,050
A classification with concrete consequences for all federal agencies using Claude directly or through third-party providers — and one that from a compliance perspective initially represents primarily an operational problem for those agencies, not just a statement about Anthropic.

16
00:02:03,050 --> 00:02:06,437
What happened next, no one had anticipated at this scale  .

17
00:02:06,437 --> 00:02:11,537
Claude climbed to #1 on the Apple App Store in over 15 countries.

18
00:02:11,537 --> 00:02:17,737
Over one million new signups daily — a trust dividend no marketing campaign could have bought.

19
00:02:17,737 --> 00:02:32,725
Analysts like Bruce Schneier and Nathan Sanders see this as more than spontaneous solidarity: the refusal to trade principles for contracts has become the strongest form of brand differentiation in a market where model performance is converging .

20
00:02:32,725 --> 00:02:41,575
When all models can compute, write and code at roughly the same level, the question "Who do I trust?" becomes the actual purchasing decision.

21
00:02:41,575 --> 00:02:46,112
The strategic calculus behind Anthropic's stance is not pure idealism .

22
00:02:46,112 --> 00:02:58,887
Enterprise customers in Europe, finance, insurance and pharmaceuticals are asking the same question that 15+ App Stores are now answering: For what purposes is this company unwilling to deploy its technology?

23
00:02:58,887 --> 00:03:05,725
Anthropic has drawn a line that may prove more valuable to these customer segments than any benchmark improvement.

24
00:03:05,725 --> 00:03:14,962
Today, March 9, 2026, the conflict escalated to the legal arena: Anthropic filed a lawsuit against the Trump administration .

25
00:03:14,962 --> 00:03:27,537
This opens a question that will work its way through the courts for months: Can a government legally compel a private company to make its technology available for specific state purposes — even against its own terms of service?

26
00:03:27,537 --> 00:03:29,975
The answer will affect more than Anthropic.

27
00:03:29,975 --> 00:03:42,687
It will set a precedent for the entire industry: whether AI labs can enforce their terms of service as a genuine protective line against government pressure — or whether they will be systematically eroded under market pressure  .

28
00:03:42,687 --> 00:03:44,025
More Top Stories.

29
00:03:44,025 --> 00:03:50,937
Claude Finds 22 Firefox Security Vulnerabilities in 14 Days — and Gives Defenders the Advantage.

30
00:03:50,937 --> 00:04:00,537
In a partnership between Anthropic and Mozilla, Claude Opus 4.6 analyzed nearly 6,000 C++ files of the Firefox browser .

31
00:04:00,537 --> 00:04:07,475
The result after two weeks: 22 security vulnerabilities identified, 14 of them high-severity.

32
00:04:07,475 --> 00:04:12,650
112 reports were submitted, most of them patched in Firefox 148.

33
00:04:12,650 --> 00:04:17,237
Claude found the first use-after-free vulnerability within 20 minutes.

34
00:04:18,162 --> 00:04:23,837
The number 14 high-severity vulnerabilities sounds abstract — until you put it in perspective .

35
00:04:23,837 --> 00:04:31,487
That amounts to nearly one-fifth of all high-severity Firefox vulnerabilities patched during the entire year 2025.

36
00:04:31,487 --> 00:04:32,650
In two weeks.

37
00:04:32,650 --> 00:04:35,550
For $4,000 in API costs.

38
00:04:35,550 --> 00:04:41,512
That is the true benchmark for this story: not speed alone, but the ratio of effort to outcome.

39
00:04:41,512 --> 00:04:47,100
Traditional security audits for a codebase of this size take months and six-figure sums.

40
00:04:47,100 --> 00:04:56,762
One caveat: independent verification of the findings by Mozilla is still pending, and the proportion of previously known vulnerabilities was not fully disclosed.

41
00:04:56,762 --> 00:05:04,025
What security experts find most notable: Claude was significantly better at finding the vulnerabilities than exploiting them .

42
00:05:04,025 --> 00:05:09,650
The project results are explicitly interpreted as: "This gives defenders the advantage."

43
00:05:09,650 --> 00:05:11,450
That is not a trivial detail.

44
00:05:11,450 --> 00:05:22,287
It means that the same tool that could theoretically help attackers works asymmetrically in favor of defense in practice — because finding is easier than exploiting, and Claude excels at finding.

45
00:05:22,287 --> 00:05:31,087
For security teams that must secure vast codebases with limited resources, this fundamentally changes the economics of defensive security.

46
00:05:31,087 --> 00:05:38,912
OpenAI GPT-5.4: 1M Context, Computer Use, 75% on OSWorld.

47
00:05:38,912 --> 00:05:46,250
OpenAI released GPT-5.4 this week in three variants: Standard, Thinking and Pro .

48
00:05:46,250 --> 00:05:54,850
The technical highlight is the 1-million-token context window as standard — not as a special feature for enterprise customers, but as the default.

49
00:05:54,850 --> 00:06:02,450
That corresponds to roughly 750,000 words or a stack of several hundred average novels in a single context.

50
00:06:02,450 --> 00:06:12,212
The OSWorld benchmark figure is the most discussed detail of the week: 75% success rate versus a human benchmark of 72.4% .

51
00:06:12,212 --> 00:06:21,500
OSWorld tests whether a model can independently execute computer-based tasks — opening windows, filling out forms, switching between applications.

52
00:06:21,500 --> 00:06:27,300
GPT-5.4 thus marginally exceeds the measured human level for the first time.

53
00:06:27,300 --> 00:06:38,137
For context: comparable benchmarks for Anthropic's Claude Sonnet 4.6 on OSWorld have not yet been fully published, which limits direct model comparisons on this basis.

54
00:06:38,137 --> 00:06:48,425
This matters for enterprise trust-building: a model that outperforms the average user in standardized computer-use tests changes the risk calculus for automated workflows.

55
00:06:48,425 --> 00:06:55,887
The 33% reduction in hallucinations compared to GPT-5.2 is the second important figure  .

56
00:06:55,887 --> 00:07:08,525
OpenAI is marketing GPT-5.4 as "its most factually accurate model to date" — a positioning aimed squarely at the enterprise segment, where reliability matters more than creativity.

57
00:07:08,525 --> 00:07:19,237
The combination of large context, computer use and reduced errors makes GPT-5.4 the most compelling argument yet for agent-based automation from OpenAI.

58
00:07:19,237 --> 00:07:28,537
The real question for organizations is not whether the model is good — but whether it is good enough to hand over processes that previously required human oversight.

59
00:07:28,537 --> 00:07:29,487
Quick Hits.

60
00:07:29,487 --> 00:07:42,762
Microsoft Copilot Cowork with Claude under the hood  — Microsoft launches Copilot Cowork as a Research Preview: an autonomous agent that plans and executes tasks across all M365 apps.

61
00:07:42,762 --> 00:07:55,837
Particularly noteworthy: Microsoft 365 Copilot Wave 3 integrates Anthropic's Claude directly into Copilot Chat — Microsoft's own models and Anthropic working within the same interface.

62
00:07:55,837 --> 00:07:59,562
Broad availability through the Frontier Program from late March.

63
00:07:59,562 --> 00:08:13,062
Gemini 3.1 Flash-Lite: Thinking at one-eighth the price  — $0.25/M input tokens, $1.50/M output — approximately one-eighth the price of Gemini 3.1 Pro.

64
00:08:13,062 --> 00:08:17,212
Four configurable thinking levels for adjustable compute intensity.

65
00:08:17,212 --> 00:08:19,037
Strong at image generation.

66
00:08:19,037 --> 00:08:29,887
For teams looking to integrate reasoning capabilities into production workflows without paying frontier model prices, this is the most affordable option with genuine reasoning budget to date.

67
00:08:30,812 --> 00:08:48,575
Qwen leadership crisis: Strong models, shaky leadership  — Alibaba's AI division releases Qwen 3.5 (0.8B–397B parameters, open-weight) — and simultaneously loses lead researcher Junyang Lin along with several key personnel.

68
00:08:48,575 --> 00:08:57,537
Technically strong, organizationally fragile: the combination raises serious questions about the long-term stability of the open-source heavyweight.

69
00:08:57,537 --> 00:09:04,925
Tool of the Week: AutoResearch — Karpathy Democratizes AI Research in 630 Lines of Python.

70
00:09:04,925 --> 00:09:16,887
Andrej Karpathy open-sourced AutoResearch this week : a 630-line Python tool that lets AI agents run fully autonomous ML experiments on a single consumer GPU.

71
00:09:16,887 --> 00:09:27,787
No multi-GPU cluster, no expensive cloud infrastructure — AutoResearch makes possible what research teams previously needed significant resources to accomplish.

72
00:09:27,787 --> 00:09:45,137
The validation example speaks for itself : According to MarkTechPost, Shopify CEO Tobi Lütke adopted AutoResearch internally and achieved a 19% improvement in validation score — using the same 630-line framework Karpathy made publicly available.

73
00:09:45,137 --> 00:09:46,962
This is not an academic demo.

74
00:09:46,962 --> 00:09:51,650
This is a production result from one of the world's largest e-commerce companies.

75
00:09:51,650 --> 00:09:56,800
What makes AutoResearch strategically interesting is its minimal-footprint philosophy .

76
00:09:56,800 --> 00:10:08,662
630 lines means: fully readable, fully adaptable, fully understandable — without framework overhead, without abstraction layers that obscure the actual experiment.

77
00:10:08,662 --> 00:10:15,837
For teams looking to systematize ML experiments with limited resources, this is an immediately usable building block.

78
00:10:15,837 --> 00:10:28,100
For the industry as a whole, Karpathy is sending a signal: the next wave of AI research will not emerge from labs with thousands of GPUs, but from developers running AutoResearch on their own machines.

79
00:10:28,100 --> 00:10:34,225
Fail of the Week: Clinejection — Prompt Injection → Cache Poisoning → NPM Secret Stolen.

80
00:10:34,225 --> 00:10:38,525
This week's story is a textbook example of multi-stage AI attacks .

81
00:10:38,525 --> 00:10:45,937
Starting point: Cline's automated GitHub issue triage bot, which processes incoming issues using Claude Code.

82
00:10:45,937 --> 00:10:53,937
The attack chain begins with a manipulated issue title — crafted precisely to function as a prompt injection when Claude Code reads it.

83
00:10:53,937 --> 00:11:00,125
The sequence in four steps : A maliciously worded issue title injects a prompt into Claude Code.

84
00:11:00,125 --> 00:11:03,600
Claude Code then executes  with a manipulated package ().

85
00:11:03,600 --> 00:11:17,825
The package injects approximately 11 GB of junk data into the GitHub Actions cache according to Willison's analysis — precisely enough to trigger the 10 GB auto-eviction threshold and introduce poisoned cache entries.

86
00:11:17,825 --> 00:11:23,812
The nightly build workflow loads the poisoned entries, exposing the NPM publishing secret.

87
00:11:23,812 --> 00:11:28,625
Result: An unauthorized  was published to npm and had to be retracted.

88
00:11:28,625 --> 00:11:31,425
The failure is structural, not individual .

89
00:11:31,425 --> 00:11:42,400
First, it demonstrates that automated AI bots processing user-generated input without sandbox isolation represent an active attack surface, not a theoretical one.

90
00:11:42,400 --> 00:11:51,337
Second: the attackers knew the GitHub Actions eviction threshold to the byte — this is not an opportunistic attack, it is targeted reconnaissance.

91
00:11:51,337 --> 00:12:01,687
Third, the damage extends beyond Cline: every unauthorized npm publication potentially endangers every project using that package as a dependency.

92
00:12:01,687 --> 00:12:10,550
The question for all teams running AI bots with write access to production systems: Where is the line between what a bot may read and what it may execute?

93
00:12:10,550 --> 00:12:14,300
Number of the Week: 4,000+.

94
00:12:14,300 --> 00:12:18,037
Source: Block/Square, neuralbuddies.com .

95
00:12:18,037 --> 00:12:26,925
That is how many positions Block CEO Jack Dorsey is cutting — citing AI automation in engineering and operations as the explicit reason.

96
00:12:26,925 --> 00:12:29,825
This is not a new number, but a new context .

97
00:12:29,825 --> 00:12:44,087
Block is thus one of the first publicly traded companies to attribute mass layoffs directly and publicly to AI — without restructuring-speak, without market conditions as the explanation, without a strategic pivot as framing.

98
00:12:44,087 --> 00:12:46,100
Just: "AI does that now."

99
00:12:46,100 --> 00:12:58,412
Several observers note, however, that the AI attribution can also be read as "AI washing" — a post-hoc rationalization for job cuts that were already planned for other economic reasons.

100
00:12:59,337 --> 00:13:04,212
What Dorsey normalizes with this is at least as significant as the number itself .

101
00:13:04,212 --> 00:13:17,225
When executives of publicly traded companies communicate AI-driven headcount reductions as direct business logic — not as a regrettable exception, but as a calculated step — societal expectations shift.

102
00:13:17,225 --> 00:13:21,575
Every company that cuts positions in the coming months can cite this precedent.

103
00:13:21,575 --> 00:13:24,550
The real question is not whether others will follow.

104
00:13:24,550 --> 00:13:31,875
The question is which industries, which job profiles and which qualification levels will be next to enter this calculation.

